# AWS Infrastructure Automation: Dynamic Networking and Compute Scaling
Task List

1. Create a VPC
   - Use CIDR block `10.0.0.0/16` to define the main network boundary.  

2. Add Subnets Dynamically
   - Instead of writing multiple subnet resources, use the `count` argument to generate `/24` subnets automatically.  
   - Example: `10.0.0.0/24`, `10.0.1.0/24`, `10.0.2.0/24`.  

3. Fetch Latest Ubuntu AMI
   - Use a Terraform `data` block to pull the newest Ubuntu 22.04 LTS image from Canonical.  
   - This avoids hardcoding AMI IDs.  

4. Control Instance Count with a Variable  
   - Define a variable `ec2_count` to decide how many EC2 instances to launch.  
   - Changing the variable changes the number of servers without touching the resource code.  

5. Distribute Instances Across Subnets
   - Use the modulo expression (`count.index % length(subnets)`) so instances are spread evenly across all subnets.  
   - This ensures high availability by placing servers in different Availability Zones.  


## Baseline Source Code

```hcl
locals {
    comon_tags={
        project="own_network"
        owner="own_terra_vpc"
    }
  
}

resource "aws_vpc" "own_vpc" {
    cidr_block = "10.0.0.0/16"

    tags = local.comon_tags

  
}
variable "ec2_count" {
    type = number
    default = 3
  
}
resource "aws_subnet" "Dynamic_subnet" {
    vpc_id     = aws_vpc.own_vpc.id
    cidr_block = "10.0.${count.index}.0/24"
    count = var.ec2_count

    tags = merge(local.comon_tags,
            
                {item_number=tostring(count.index)},
                {full_details="${local.comon_tags.owner}-${count.index}"},
                {Name="own-tera-subnet-${count.index}"}
            )
  
}
resource "aws_instance" "ex1" {
  count = var.ec2_count
  ami           = data.aws_ami.own_ami_ubuntu_IND.id
  instance_type = "t2.micro"
  
  subnet_id = aws_subnet.Dynamic_subnet[count.index].id
  tags = {
    Name="own-tera-instance-${count.index}"
  }
}

data "aws_ami" "own_ami_ubuntu_IND" {
  most_recent = true
  owners      = ["099720109477"] # Canonical's AWS account ID

  filter {
    name   = "name"
    values = ["ubuntu/images/hvm-ssd/ubuntu-jammy-22.04-amd64-server-*"]
  }

  filter {
    name   = "virtualization-type"
    values = ["hvm"]
  }
}

```

